  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Mauritania: Seeking ways to strengthen its human rights defenders</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Mauritania&apos;s civil society is a key actor in promoting development and human rights, but its work is undermined by e.g. government restrictions, intimidations, harassment and smear campaigns, especially when addressing issues related to discrimination, gender, and religion. At the end of November 2017, AINL/HURICAP undertook a scoping mission to Mauritania to identify potential partners that would benefit most from our capacity-building work. Yet, the mission could not be fulfilled as Amnesty staff was - upon arrival - not allowed into the country. In 2018, the identification of potential partners continued through online meetings with various human rights organisations and defenders. A first training was held in Tunisia in 2018. Yet, after this training, different parties involved could not agree on the direction any follow up programme should take (as a result of different interests, needs, etc). As a result, the programme was halted in early 2019.</narrative>
  </description>
